Good question to dig into — this kind of misreading is common and usually traces back to a few specific habits.

1. "There must exist a positive integer f" — you read f as "an element of the array" instead of "a frequency value"

The phrase "positive integer" is generic, so your brain pattern-matched it to the array elements (which are also positive integers) rather than to an abstract count. The word "frequency" appears right before, but your eyes likely jumped past it because it's a description of f's role, not announced as boldly as "f is the frequency."

Fix for next time: when a problem says "there exists an integer X such that [condition involving counts/occurrences]", explicitly ask yourself — is X a value from the array, an index, or a derived quantity (like a count)? Underline or rewrite it in your own words before coding: "f = some count; every element's occurrence-count must be f or 2f."

2. "Both frequencies occur among the distinct values" — you dropped the word "both"

This sentence is the one that converts it from an OR condition to an AND condition. If you skim past "both", the constraint silently weakens from "f and 2f must both appear as frequencies" to "frequencies must be f or 2f" (each individually fine, no co-occurrence required). This is a classic case of a single quantifier word (both, all, any, exactly, at least one) carrying the entire logical weight of the sentence — and it's easy to read past because it's short and unstressed.

Fix: for constraint-heavy problems, try to translate the English into a tiny formal statement before coding:

Your reading: ∀ value v, freq(v) ∈ {f, 2f} — this is actually consistent with what you thought, but it allows the degenerate case where all frequencies equal f (then 2f never appears) or all equal 2f.
Actual problem: ∀ value v, freq(v) ∈ {f, 2f} AND f appears at least once AND 2f appears at least once.
The first formula alone is almost satisfied by any set of frequencies (since you can usually pick f to be the smallest one and everything could trivially be "f or 2f" in degenerate single-frequency cases) — so "both" is the clause doing the real filtering work.

3. General debugging strategy for "misread the problem" issues

After reading the problem once, write a one-line formal/mathematical restatement of the core condition before touching code. If you can't write it precisely, you haven't understood it yet.
Test your restatement against all given examples manually — especially the ones that seem to demonstrate edge cases (Example 2 with all-same-value, Example 3 with all-distinct) — these examples often exist specifically to disambiguate the exact reading you got wrong.
Pay special attention to quantifier words: both, all, any, exactly, at least, exists, every, only. These single words often flip the entire meaning of a constraint, and they're the most "skimmable" words in a sentence because they're short and grammatically unstressed.
This isn't really a DSA skill gap — it's a "read mathematically, not narratively" skill, and it gets better with deliberate practice of restating conditions formally before coding.

