Walking through the Java solution:

Overall structure

Two nested loops generate every subarray: i is the start, j extends the end one step at a time. For each (i, j), we maintain the frequency information of nums[i..j] incrementally, then check the balance condition in O(1).

The two maps

freq: maps value → how many times it appears in the current window nums[i..j].

freqOfFreq: maps frequency → how many distinct values currently have that frequency. This is the key trick — instead of recomputing "what are the distinct frequency values?" from scratch each time (which would be O(distinct elements)), we maintain a running count.

Inner loop, step by step

When we extend the window to include nums[j] = x:

java
int old = freq.getOrDefault(x, 0);
int updated = old + 1;
old is x's frequency before adding this occurrence; updated is after.

java
if (old > 0) {
    int c = freqOfFreq.get(old);
    if (c == 1) freqOfFreq.remove(old);
    else freqOfFreq.put(old, c - 1);
}
If x already had a frequency (old > 0), that frequency bucket in freqOfFreq loses one member (x is moving from frequency old to old+1). If that bucket becomes empty, remove it entirely so freqOfFreq.size() stays accurate.

java
freq.put(x, updated);
freqOfFreq.put(updated, freqOfFreq.getOrDefault(updated, 0) + 1);
Update x's frequency to updated, and add x to the updated bucket in freqOfFreq.

Example of this bookkeeping

Say x previously occurred 2 times (old=2), now occurs 3 times (updated=3):

Remove x from freqOfFreq[2] (decrement or delete that entry).
Add x to freqOfFreq[3] (increment that entry, or create it).
So freqOfFreq always tells you: "right now, how many distinct array-values have frequency 1? frequency 2? etc." — without ever re-scanning freq.

