More than one distinct value exists. freqOfFreq.size() == 2 means exactly two different frequency values are present among all elements — that's the "both f and 2f occur" requirement, since if all elements shared one frequency, freqOfFreq.size() would be 1, and that case is excluded here (it would fail the b == 2*a check trivially anyway, but more importantly the problem requires both to be present).

We extract the two frequency values a and b, sort them so a ≤ b, and check b == 2*a — i.e., the larger frequency is exactly double the smaller. That's the f and 2f condition (a = f, b = 2f).

If both checks pass, this window length is a candidate for best.

Why freqOfFreq.size() == 2 correctly encodes "both f and 2f present, and nothing else"

If freqOfFreq.size() == 1: every element has the same frequency. Only valid if that single frequency could be both f and 2f simultaneously — impossible unless f = 2f, i.e., f = 0, which isn't a positive integer. So correctly excluded.
If freqOfFreq.size() == 2: exactly two frequency values exist — check if they're in a 1:2 ratio.
If freqOfFreq.size() >= 3: three or more distinct frequencies exist, which can never fit the "only f or 2f" constraint. Correctly excluded.
